Content: "WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. President Donald Trump on Friday took the first step in his campaign to ditch the Obamacare individual mandate, a piece of the law that he wants to remove from the law without a Republican replacement. Trump said he was “totally opposed” to the law and he did not want to end the requirement and that it was a mistake. “Let’s not get into the silly politics of replacing it as an idea, because he did a foolish thing,” Trump said at the White House. Trump has talked about using the law to push through a repeal. The Democratic president, Barack Obama, proposed replacing the mandate with a fixed tax credit known as a credit for the cost of private insurance. The current law gives insurance plans, for example, $5,800 for individuals and $11,000 for family members.  “The Affordable Care Act is a big mistake,” Trump said. Trump said the law had let the government too easily determine premiums. “That has to change,” he said.  ",<|endoftext|>
